│ addCanonicalIVRecipes function removes the branch-on-cond in the latch      │
│ (line 436). That's correct.\n\nBut what about the early exit? That should   │
│ be handled by vectorizing the condition and creating an early exit path.    │
│ The issue is that when we have an early exit, we need to compute which      │
│ iteration caused the exit.\n\nLooking at the generated IR in the", "tgt":   │
│ "ection, I see:\n```\n  %5 = icmp ne i8 %3, 0\n  %6 = icmp ne i8 %4, 0\n    │
│ %index.next = add nuw i32 %index, 2\n  %7 = freeze i1 %5\n  %8 = freeze i1  │
│ %6\n  %9 = or i1 %7, %8\n  %10 = icmp eq i32 %index.next, 4\n  %11 = or i1  │
│ %9, %10\n  br i1 %11, label %middle.split, label %vector.body, !llvm.loop   │
│ !0\n```\n\nSo it ORs the conditions from both lanes, and also ORs with the  │
│ normal exit condition (index.next == 4). If any is true, it goes to         │
│ middle.split. Then in middle.split:\n```\n  br i1 %9, label                 │
│ %vector.early.exit, label %middle.block\n```\n\nIf %9 (the OR of early exit │
│ conditions) is true, go to vector.early.exit, else to middle.block.\n\nIn   │
│ vector.early.exit, it uses offset.idx (the index from the vector            │
│ iteration). But which offset.idx? It should be the first lane that          │
│ triggered the exit. The code uses offset.idx#phi#0 which is the offset.idx  │
│ from the vector.body that exited. But that's the base index of the vector   │
│ iteration, not the specific lane index.\n\nActually, looking at the         │
